I worry that perhaps nobody knows how mergers work. Not in like a =E2=80=9C=
let me tell you=E2=80=9D sense, but in an =E2=80=9Ceverything is fundamenta=
lly unknowable=E2=80=9D sense. Lots of contracts between companies have pro=
visions that say that the companies can=E2=80=99t transfer them to someone =
else. If you hire McKinsey & Co. to do some consulting for you, you don=E2=
=80=99t want Joe=E2=80=99s Consulting to show up for the engagement and say=
 =E2=80=9Coh yeah we bought this contract from McKinsey, that=E2=80=99s fin=
e right?=E2=80=9D So the contract will say that neither side can assign its=
 rights and obligations under the contract to anyone else.
So an incredibly basic=C2=A0question in mergers and acquisitions is: If we =
acquire Company X, do we keep all of its contracts? Or do those contracts h=
ave =E2=80=9Canti-assignment=E2=80=9D provisions that would be triggered by=
 an acquisition?
From first principles, you=E2=80=99d think that most of the contracts shoul=
d continue without interruption. If you rent some office space to Company X=
 and it gets acquired by another company, not much has changed=C2=A0for you=
:=C2=A0The same people come to the same office to do the same work, and the=
y pay you the same rent with checks drawn on the same account. If you licen=
