Elsewhere in =E2=80=9Cnobody knows how _____ work=E2=80=9D: Really nobody k=
nows how convertible bonds work. I mean, a lot of people have the general i=
dea (they=E2=80=99re bonds that can convert into stock). But they are=C2=A0=
somewhat weird instruments with odd nooks and crannies, and, while they are=
 not rare, neither are they all that common. Lots of companies will never d=
o a convertible in their lives. Generally financially literate people =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0chief financial officers and corporate treasurers, industry inv=
estment bankers =E2=80=94=C2=A0will probably have a decent working knowledg=
e of bond deals and bank loans and stock offerings and mergers, because the=
y come up a lot; they might be less familiar with convertibles.
I, on the other hand, used to be a convertible=C2=A0bond investment banker,=
 so I have somewhat more than the usual familiarity with them. I=C2=A0could=
 tell you, for instance, that it is common in the US for a convertible to b=
e done as a Rule 144A offering, meaning that the bonds are sold to large =
=E2=80=9Cqualified institutional buyers=E2=80=9D (QIBs) in a private placem=
ent=C2=A0and then can=E2=80=99t be resold to retail investors. Doing a 144A=
 deal is generally faster and cheaper than doing a public deal that is regi=
stered with the US Securities and Exchange Commission, and retail investors=
 don=E2=80=99t really buy convertibles anyway.
But eventually the institutional buyers of a 144A deal will want to be able=
 to convert their bonds into regular, publicly traded stock, so there needs=
 to be some mechanism for turning =E2=80=9C144A=E2=80=9D convertibles into =
=E2=80=9Cregistered=E2=80=9D ones. I am old enough that, when I started as =
a converts banker, the way to do this was to file a registration statement =
with the SEC, but the modern approach is pretty much that you wait six mont=
hs or a year=C2=A0and the convertible becomes freely tradeable as a legal m=
atter.
  [3]

As a=C2=A0practical=C2=A0matter, though, the way this works is that the bon=
ds, when they are originally issued, have a =E2=80=9Crestrictive legend=E2=
=80=9D on them saying that they can be sold only to institutional buyers, a=
nd after a year the company sends a notice to its transfer agent saying =E2=
=80=9Cyou can take that legend off the bonds now.=E2=80=9D And when the bon=
ds have the legend, they can=E2=80=99t be freely traded; once the legend is=
 off, they can be. Here I am pretending, as one does, that =E2=80=9Cthe bon=
ds=E2=80=9D are pieces of paper with a legend stamped on them, but of cours=
e they are actually entries in an electronic database; what=C2=A0really=C2=
=A0happens is that the original bonds have a =E2=80=9Crestricted CUSIP=E2=
=80=9D (the  identification number that every security has), telling transf=
er agents and depositaries and brokers and everyone else that they can only=
 be sold to QIBs, and then after a year the company gets them a new =E2=80=
=9Cunrestricted CUSIP=E2=80=9D and they trade freely. This is not hard =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s a phone call or an email, maybe a legal opinion =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the company has to do it.
It is good, for the bondholders, to get unrestricted bonds, though it doesn=
=E2=80=99t matter that=C2=A0much, since they=E2=80=99re really only trading=
 with other institutional buyers anyway. And so in the documents for the co=
nvertible bond, there will be a provision saying that, after a year, the co=
mpany has to make the convertible unrestricted (by removing the restrictive=
 legend=C2=A0and getting an unrestricted CUSIP). If it doesn=E2=80=99t do t=
hat, it has to pay some extra interest=C2=A0to compensate the bondholders a=
