during the 46 minutes that the stock traded at =E2=80=9Cartificially inflat=
ed=E2=80=9D prices.
=E2=80=9CTo company insiders who were responsible for ensuring the accuracy=
 of the press release and supplemental data, the misrepresentation was so a=
pparent that it went beyond mere negligence, and amounted to a reckless ind=
ifference to the truth,=E2=80=9D Chen=E2=80=99s lawyers wrote in the compla=
int.

To   quote Lyft=E2=80=99s chief executive officer: =E2=80=9CIt was one zero=
 in a press release.=E2=80=9D On the second page. The theory in this lawsui=
t =E2=80=94=C2=A0here is  the complaint =E2=80=94=C2=A0appears to be that L=
yft=E2=80=99s executives=C2=A0knew=C2=A0the press release was wrong, but th=
ey=C2=A0wanted=C2=A0to mislead the market =E2=80=94=C2=A0for 46 minutes of =
after-hours trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0because =E2=80=A6=C2=A0? Because they we=
re=C2=A0=E2=80=9Centitled to substantial performance based executive compen=
sation based on Lyft common stock achieving certain price-based benchmarks,=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe presence of a large short position in Lyft commo=
n stock is an impediment to [their] ability to achieve those performance ba=
sed benchmarks=E2=80=9D? And so they tried to conduct some sort of brief af=
ter-hours short squeeze to push up the stock and get paid on their options?=
 I don=E2=80=99t even know what to tell you. The complaint is wild:
To company insiders who were familiar with Lyft=E2=80=99s historical and an=
ticipated operating results, the misstatement in the press release and Supp=
lemental Data would have stuck out =E2=80=9Clike a sore thumb.=E2=80=9D
One zero!

Bloomberg lists 35 separate stock analysts who provide active coverage of L=
yft common stock.
It is highly likely, if not certain, that one or more of those analysts =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or=C2=A0other investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0contacted the Defendants=
 or other Lyft personnel in the minutes immediately after the issue of the =
press release to obtain clarification on the 500 basis point margin expansi=
on.
Thus, Defendants knew or were almost certain to know of the misstatement on=
 or shortly after 4:05 p.m. on February 13, 2024.

I feel like=C2=A0this=C2=A0theory of efficient markets goes too far? =E2=80=
=9CIf there=E2=80=99s a typo in the adjusted EBITDA margin forecast in the =
second page of an earnings release from a widely followed company, eagle-ey=
ed analysts will spot it within minutes and call the company to correct it.=
=E2=80=9D I know that I often say around here that =E2=80=9Ceverything is s=
ecurities fraud,=E2=80=9D but I=C2=A0have   already said that this wasn=E2=
=80=99t, and I think I=E2=80=99ll stick to that.

 =20
   =20
      Fake bankruptcy!
   =20
 =20

The  classic move is: You buy stock in a company, you put out a fake press =
release saying that you =E2=80=94=C2=A0or Amalgamated Amalgamators Inc., or=
 Warren Buffett =E2=80=94=C2=A0have proposed to acquire the company at a 50=
% premium to its current price, automated news-writing algorithms pick up y=
our press release, automated trading algorithms buy stock, the stock goes u=
p, you=C2=A0sell=C2=A0your stock at a profit, and everyone pretty quickly r=
ealizes it=E2=80=99s a hoax and the stock goes down again. There are two pr=
oblems with this:
=09It is illegal and you=E2=80=99ll probably get caught.=09While it technic=
ally=C2=A0works, in the sense that you can pretty reliably generate a brief=
 small stock-price pop with a fake merger announcement, people who=C2=A0act=
ually do it=C2=A0have an absolutely bizarre track record of messing it up a=
nd not making any money on it. It is baffling to me, but they put all this =
work into filing fake press releases and then forget to sell their stock wh=
ile it=E2=80=99s up. I  wrote in 2015 about an accused serial fake-merger h=
oaxer who, according to the US Securities and Exchange Commission complaint=
 against him, manipulated three different stocks with fake mergers and lost=
 money on each one of them. And we  talked a few months ago about a guy who=
 allegedly did a hoax merger manipulation on WeWork Inc. just before it fil=
ed for bankruptcy, but who put out the fake press release after market hour=
s and so couldn=E2=80=99t sell his stock at a profit =E2=80=94=C2=A0in fact=
, couldn=E2=80=99t sell it at all before the bankruptcy filing.

If=C2=A0I were=C2=A0doing a merger hoax, I would put out the fake press rel=
ease at like 10:29 a.m. and then=C2=A0sit at my computer for five minutes, =
with my brokerage account website open, ready to hit the =E2=80=9Csell=E2=
=80=9D button as soon as the price went up. (Not legal, or illegal, advice.=
) But for some reason nobody ever executes this trade correctly.
The inverse trade is: You=C2=A0short=C2=A0stock in a company (or buy puts, =
etc.), you make a=C2=A0fake bankruptcy filing on behalf of the company, aut=
omated news-writing algorithms pick up the filing and report that the compa=
ny is bankrupt, automated trading algorithms sell the stock, the stock goes=
 down, you cover your short at a profit, and everyone pretty quickly realiz=
es it=E2=80=99s a hoax and the stock goes up again. This however suffers fr=
om the same two problems, namely:
=09You will get in trouble.=09You will mess it up.

Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Jonathan Randles and Steven Church report:

A Buffalo man identified in court papers as Robert W. Johnson =E2=80=94 who=
 sometimes goes by Willie =E2=80=94 has filed bankruptcy petitions on behal=
f of two different publicly traded companies in recent months despite havin=
g no authority or basis to do so. Public policy in the US makes them tough =
to stamp out completely, leaving a confusing trail of public denials and qu=
ick dismissals in their wake.
He first took aim at Carrols Restaurant Group, the largest Burger King fran=
chisee in the US, in early February. Shoddy assembly of the snail-mailed pe=
titions didn=E2=80=99t stop them from appearing in official court dockets, =
however briefly. Then, in recent days he targeted NerdWallet, a personal fi=
nance firm with a market value of more than $1 billion. NerdWallet called t=
he filing =E2=80=9Cfraudulent and unauthorized=E2=80=9D and a judge tossed =
the petition shortly after.
Even the brief existence of such fake filings can trigger computer-driven c=
ourt filing scrapers, leaving incorrect impressions on court watchers inclu=
ding Bloomberg News. Both of Johnson=E2=80=99s filings showed up outside of=
 stock market hours, but NerdWallet=E2=80=99s shares still fell for a time =
when trading opened on Monday.

=E2=80=9CSnail-mailed=E2=80=9D! How are you going to trade on that?

