<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I worry that perhaps nobody knows how mergers =
work. Not in like a =E2=80=9Clet me tell you=E2=80=9D sense, but in an =E2=
=80=9Ceverything is fundamentally unknowable=E2=80=9D sense. Lots of contra=
cts between companies have provisions that say that the companies can=E2=80=
=99t transfer them to someone else. If you hire McKinsey &amp; Co. to do so=
me consulting for you, you don=E2=80=99t want Joe=E2=80=99s Consulting to s=
how up for the engagement and say =E2=80=9Coh yeah we bought this contract =
from McKinsey, that=E2=80=99s fine right?=E2=80=9D So the contract will say=
 that neither side can assign its rights and obligations under the contract=
 to anyone else.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So an <em>incredibly basic=C2=A0</em>question =
in mergers and acquisitions is: If we acquire Company X, do we keep all of =
its contracts? Or do those contracts have =E2=80=9Canti-assignment=E2=80=9D=
 provisions that would be triggered by an acquisition?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From first principles, you=E2=80=99d think tha=
t most of the contracts should continue without interruption. If you rent s=
ome office space to Company X and it gets acquired by another company, not =
much has changed=C2=A0<em>for you:=C2=A0</em>The same people come to the sa=
me office to do the same work, and they pay you the same rent with checks d=
rawn on the same account. If you license some software from Company X and i=
t gets acquired, it=E2=80=99s still the same software.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the contracts continue uninterrupted when t=
he company is acquired, that generally makes life simpler for the company=
=E2=80=99s customers and suppliers and landlords. Also, though, it makes me=
rgers and acquisitions=C2=A0<em>possible</em>. If every company lost all of=
 its office leases and customers and supply deals and employment contracts =
when it was acquired, who would want to acquire it? A company mostly=C2=A0<=
em>is=C2=A0</em>a big pile of contracts; if an acquisition terminated all o=
f those contracts then there would be no acquisitions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most of the time this is the right answer and=
=C2=A0works out fine. Most big public mergers and acquisitions, for instanc=
e, are structured in ways that preserve=C2=A0the target company intact, wit=
h the buyer owning its=C2=A0stock. (For instance, in a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuaW52ZXN0b3BlZGlhLmNvbS90ZXJtcy9yL3J0bS5hc3AjOn46dGV4dD1BJTIwcmV2ZXJzZSUy=
MHRyaWFuZ3VsYXIlMjBtZXJnZXIlMjBpcyxhYnNvcmJlZCUyMGJ5JTIwdGhlJTIwdGFyZ2V0JTI=
wY29tcGFueS4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb1ff7ead" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">reverse triangular =
merger</a>=E2=80=9D in which a subsidiary of the buyer merges with the targ=
et, which survives the merger as a subsidiary of the buyer.) A contract tha=
t says =E2=80=9CCompany X can=E2=80=99t transfer this contract to anyone el=
se=E2=80=9D should not be affected by this sort of deal: Company X <em>hasn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>transferred the contract to anyone else; Company X is =
still doing the contract; it=E2=80=99s just that Company X has a new owner.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But probably there are some contracts where th=
at doesn=E2=80=99t make sense, where an acquisition of the company should g=
ive the counterparty a right to get out of the contract. If you have a huge=
 deal to sell a sensitive product to some trusted customer, and then that c=
ustomer gets acquired by your biggest rival, or in a leveraged buyout that =
makes it less creditworthy, or by a sanctioned foreign company, you will be=
 unhappy and think that the deal is no longer what you signed up for. And s=
o some contracts will say something like =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t transfe=
r this contract, and just to be clear,=C2=A0if you get acquired in a merger=
 we can also get out of the contract.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine contracts just saying this c=
learly. Like, every contract could say either:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CNeither company can transfer=
 or assign this contract, but obviously if the company is acquired in a mer=
ger that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s not a transfer.=E2=80=9D Or,</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CNeither company can transfer =
or assign this contract, and if the company is acquired in a merger that al=
so counts as a transfer and is not allowed.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, you=E2=80=99d have to wo=
rk on the language. There are lots of more complicated ways to acquire a co=
mpany, different ways to structure mergers or buy control or gain influence=
 on the board or whatever; specifying exactly what you mean could take some=
 work.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in actual fact the world seems to be consi=
derably messier than that. There are all sorts of contracts with all sorts =
of language, and a lot of them do not make it=C2=A0<em>obvious=C2=A0</em>wh=
ether the company can do a merger and keep the contract.=C2=A0Here is a sor=
t of horrifying <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34=
603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibG9nLmZyZXNoZmllbGRzLnVzL3Bvc3QvMTAyZ2ZtNi9kZWxhd=
2FyZS1jb3VydC1ob2xkcy1hbnRpLWFzc2lnbm1lbnQtY2xhdXNlLXByZXZlbnRzLWVuZm9yY2Vt=
ZW50LW9mLWNvbnRyYWN0LWFmdGU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB13e9a1a1" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> law=
-firm blog post</a> about a 2020 court decision in Delaware finding that a =
contract that says it can=E2=80=99t be assigned =E2=80=9Cby operation of la=
w or otherwise=E2=80=9D does not survive a <em>forward </em>triangular merg=
er, which is different from=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>Delaware decisions fin=
ding that =E2=80=9Canti-assignment clauses containing both a prohibition on=
 assignment =E2=80=98by operation of law=E2=80=99=C2=A0and a reference to =
=E2=80=98successors=E2=80=99 were ambiguous=E2=80=9D about mergers. You get=
 the sense that there are a lot of contracts out there where one side think=
s =E2=80=9Cthis contract terminates on a merger=E2=80=9D and the other side=
 doesn=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hess Corp. is an oil company. <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2=
VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzQ0NDcvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMjYwMjgzL2Q1NTg4M=
TZkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB47e7872d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Last October</a=
>, it signed a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/346=
03555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0vQXJjaG=
l2ZXMvZWRnYXIvZGF0YS8wMDAwMDkzNDEwLzAwMDExOTMxMjUyNDA0NjIyMy9kNTc2MTU5ZHM0L=
mh0bSNhbm5leGFjb3Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01c7877d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> merger agree=
ment</a> to be acquired by Chevron Corp. in a reverse triangular merger. Li=
ke a lot of oil companies, Hess owns partial stakes in several oil fields, =
which it shares with other oil companies under joint venture agreements. So=
me joint venture agreements have provisions saying that Hess can=E2=80=99t =
transfer its interests in those fields without giving its partners a right =
of first refusal to buy out Hess=E2=80=99s=C2=A0interests. You could imagin=
e those provisions applying to mergers (oil projects are pretty fraught, He=
ss=E2=80=99s=C2=A0partners don=E2=80=99t want to suddenly end up partners w=
ith some other, more geopolitically undesirable company), or you could imag=
ine them=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>applying to mergers (if an oil company lost=
 all of its oil projects when it was acquired, who would want to acquire it=
?). Either way, you could imagine these provisions being=C2=A0<em>very care=
fully negotiated and drafted</em>, so that everyone was very clear on wheth=
er or not Hess could keep the joint ventures if it was acquired.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or totally not! Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMDYvZXh4b24tZmlsZXMtYXJ=
iaXRyYXRpb24tdG8tcHJvdGVjdC1ndXlhbmEtZmlyc3QtcmVmdXNhbC1yaWdodHM_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDMwNzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB32399247" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  Kevin Crowley reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon Mobil Corp. filed for arbitration to ret=
ain pre-emption rights in a giant Guyanese oil field, threatening Chevron C=
orp.=E2=80=99s attempt to acquire a stake via its pending $53 billion takeo=
ver of Hess Corp.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon filed for arbitration in the Internation=
al Chamber of Commerce in Paris on Wednesday, Senior Vice President Neil Ch=
apman said during a Morgan Stanley conference. Exxon, as 45% owner and oper=
ator of the Guyana project, believes it has a right of first refusal over a=
ny change of hands in Hess=E2=80=99 30% stake and would consider matching C=
hevron=E2=80=99s valuation, he said. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chevron=E2=80=99s deal to buy Hess amounts to =
a circumvention of Exxon=E2=80=99s pre-emption rights, Chapman said. While =
the joint-operating agreement with Hess and other partners in Guyana is con=
fidential, Exxon is =E2=80=9Cvery, very confident=E2=80=9D in its position,=
 he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe understand the intent of this lang=
uage of the whole contract because we wrote it,=E2=80=9D Chapman said. =E2=
=80=9CThe Chevron-Hess transaction, what it really did, is it attempted to =
circumvent the commercial purpose=E2=80=9D of the agreement.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe! Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMDYvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYmV0LWNoZXZy=
b24tb3ZlcmNvbWVzLWV4eG9uLW1vdmUtdG8tY2xvc2UtaGVzcy1kZWFsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDc=
yNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV=
90ZXJtPTI0MDMwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
3d28ce2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  Yiqin Shen, Dinesh Nair and Swetha Gopinath also report<=
/a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge fund managers that wagered billions on C=
hevron Corp.=E2=80=99s October deal to buy Hess Corp. are sticking to their=
 bets despite another roadblock that could potentially torpedo the acquisit=
ion. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CChevron has made it clear that it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t think the right of first refusal issue is applicable, and most=
 investors seemed to have gotten around to that view,=E2=80=9D said Frederi=
c Boucher, a risk-arbitrage analyst at Susquehanna Financial Group, which i=
s a market maker in Hess=E2=80=99s securities. Chevron said last week that =
it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfully committed=E2=80=9D to the Hess deal and doesn=
=E2=80=99t believe the contract or discussions with Exxon will prevent its =
completion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Exxon thinks that the joint operating agreemen=
t for the Stabroek block off Guyana gives it a right of first refusal (ROFR=
) over any transfer of Hess=E2=80=99s stake in the block, including by a me=
rger in which Hess is acquired. Hess and Chevron think it doesn=E2=80=99t a=
pply to mergers; they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0=
vQXJjaGl2ZXMvZWRnYXIvZGF0YS85MzQxMC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjQwNDYyMjMvZDU3NjE1OWRzNC=
5odG0jdG9jNTc2MTU5XzM4YQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbf731089" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> say in=
 their merger proxy</a> that =E2=80=9CChevron and Hess believe that the Sta=
broek ROFR does not apply to the merger due to the structure of the merger =
and the language of the Stabroek ROFR provisions.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CT<span>=
here is no possible scenario in which Exxon or CNOOC could acquire Hess=E2=
=80=99 interest in Guyana as a result of the Chevron-Hess transaction,=E2=
=80=9D Hess <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/346035=
55.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzQ0NDcvMDAwM=
TE5MzEyNTI0MDYxNTMwL2Q4MDYyMjJkNDI1Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB446094d1=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> told its</a> employees yesterday.</span></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of these are big serious companies with go=
od lawyers who have written these contracts before. Chevron=E2=80=99s <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0vQXJjaGl2ZXMvZWRnYXIvZGF0YS=
85MzQxMC8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjQwNDYyMjMvZDU3NjE1OWRzNC5odG0jdHg1NzYxNTlfNA/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB4f65f4c1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proposed acquisition of Hess</a>=C2=
=A0is as straightforward as can be, a completely standard all-stock reverse=
 triangular merger; there is no weird structuring here to either get around=
 or trigger the right of first refusal. It=E2=80=99s a simple question: Doe=
s the right of first refusal apply to a normal merger of Hess? Exxon seems =
confident that it does; Chevron and Hess seem confident that it does not.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weird stuff. I <em>obviously=C2=A0</em>cannot =
tell you who is right.=C2=A0The language of the Stabroek joint operating ag=
reement is not public, and neither is the arbitration filing, so I don=E2=
=80=99t know what the contract says, and even if I did I probably wouldn=E2=
=80=99t be sure what it <em>means</em>. The people who=C2=A0<em>wrote=C2=A0=
</em>it aren=E2=80=99t sure!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, I see the arbitrageurs=E2=80=99 point. =
=E2=80=9CWe owe it to our investors and partners to consider our preemption=
 rights,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQ=
tMDMtMDYvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYmV0LWNoZXZyb24tb3ZlcmNvbWVzLWV4eG9uLW1vdmUtdG8tY2=
xvc2UtaGVzcy1kZWFsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMDcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1ha=
WwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9u=
ZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc3d28ce2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says Exxon</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOTkxOTBmZTktNzAwNS00NmIyLTkyNTEtN2IxOGMwYmM0Y=
2M1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd2c65cfc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> and</a>: =E2=80=9CThe pre-e=
mption rights are to give us the opportunity to look at the value, which we=
 can then match should we choose to do so.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It is <em>consider=
ing options</em>, not=C2=A0<em>actually offering to buy the stake</em>. Buy=
ing the stake would be expensive,=C2=A0arguably more expensive for Exxon th=
an for Chevron because it would have to gross Hess up for taxes.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> On the other hand, for Exxon, filing for arbitration to delay the Chev=
ron/Hess deal (and cast some doubt on its ability to close) is just good bu=
siness! At worst, you make life annoying for two competitors. At best, they=
 write you a large check to go away and let them close their deal. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMDYvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMt=
YmV0LWNoZXZyb24tb3ZlcmNvbWVzLWV4eG9uLW1vdmUtdG8tY2xvc2UtaGVzcy1kZWFsP2NtcGl=
kPUJCRDAzMDcyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbG=
V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cDc3d28ce2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Also</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The possibility that Exxon might e=
ventually make a bid for Hess outright might have contributed to the [merge=
r arbitrage] spread narrowing, Boucher added.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Exxon just acquired Hess itself, I guess th=
is joint venture wouldn=E2=80=99t be a problem.</p>
