<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere in =E2=80=9Cnobody knows how _____ w=
ork=E2=80=9D: <em>Really</em> nobody knows how convertible bonds work. I me=
an, a lot of people have the general idea (they=E2=80=99re bonds that can c=
onvert into stock). But they are=C2=A0somewhat weird instruments with odd n=
ooks and crannies, and, while they are not <em>rare</em>, neither are they =
all that common. Lots of companies will never do a convertible in their liv=
es. Generally financially literate people =E2=80=94=C2=A0chief financial of=
ficers and corporate treasurers, industry investment bankers =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0will probably have a decent working knowledge of bond deals and bank loa=
ns and stock offerings and mergers, because they come up a lot; they might =
be less familiar with convertibles.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I, on the other hand, used to be a convertible=
=C2=A0bond investment banker, so I have somewhat more than the usual famili=
arity with them. I=C2=A0could tell you, for instance, that it is common in =
the US for a convertible to be done as a Rule 144A offering, meaning that t=
he bonds are sold to large =E2=80=9Cqualified institutional buyers=E2=80=9D=
 (QIBs) in a private placement=C2=A0and then can=E2=80=99t be resold to ret=
ail investors. Doing a 144A deal is generally faster and cheaper than doing=
 a public deal that is registered with the US Securities and Exchange Commi=
ssion, and retail investors don=E2=80=99t really buy convertibles anyway.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But eventually the institutional buyers of a 1=
44A deal will want to be able to convert their bonds into regular, publicly=
 traded stock, so there needs to be some mechanism for turning =E2=80=9C144=
A=E2=80=9D convertibles into =E2=80=9Cregistered=E2=80=9D ones. I am old en=
ough that, when I started as a converts banker, the way to do this was to f=
ile a registration statement with the SEC, but the modern approach is prett=
y much that you wait six months or a year=C2=A0and the convertible becomes =
freely tradeable as a legal matter.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a=C2=A0<em>practical=C2=A0</em>matter, thou=
gh, the way this works is that the bonds, when they are originally issued, =
have a =E2=80=9Crestrictive legend=E2=80=9D on them saying that they can be=
 sold only to institutional buyers, and after a year the company sends a no=
tice to its transfer agent saying =E2=80=9Cyou can take that legend off the=
 bonds now.=E2=80=9D And when the bonds have the legend, they can=E2=80=99t=
 be freely traded; once the legend is off, they can be. Here I am pretendin=
g, as one does, that =E2=80=9Cthe bonds=E2=80=9D are pieces of paper with a=
 legend stamped on them, but of course they are actually entries in an elec=
tronic database; what=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>happens is that the origina=
l bonds have a =E2=80=9Crestricted CUSIP=E2=80=9D (the <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWJhLm=
NvbS9hYm91dC11cy9vdXItc3RvcnkvY3VzaXAtc2VjdXJpdGllcy1pZGVudGlmaWNhdGlvbiM6f=
jp0ZXh0PUNVU0lQJUMyJUFFJTIwaXMlMjB0aGUlMjB1bml2ZXJzYWxseSxmb3IlMjB0aGUlMjBV=
UyUyMGFuZCUyMENhbmFkYS4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB125f6683" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> identif=
ication number</a> that every security has), telling transfer agents and de=
positaries and brokers and everyone else that they can only be sold to QIBs=
, and then after a year the company gets them a new =E2=80=9Cunrestricted C=
USIP=E2=80=9D and they trade freely. This is not hard =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=
=80=99s a phone call or an email, maybe a legal opinion =E2=80=94=C2=A0but =
the company has to do it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is good, for the bondholders, to get unrest=
ricted bonds, though it doesn=E2=80=99t matter <em>that=C2=A0</em>much, sin=
ce they=E2=80=99re really only trading with other institutional buyers anyw=
ay. And so in the documents for the convertible bond, there will be a provi=
sion saying that, after a year, the company has to make the convertible unr=
estricted (by removing the restrictive legend=C2=A0and getting an unrestric=
ted CUSIP). If it doesn=E2=80=99t do that, it has to pay some extra interes=
t=C2=A0to compensate the bondholders and to incentivize the company to get =
its act together.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So for instance here is <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdv=
di9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzcwNDU2Mi8wMDAxNjgzMTY4MjEwMDA5MjMvYXZpZF9leDA=
0MDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6062cc35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the indenture</a> for =
Avid Bioservices=C2=A0Inc.=E2=80=99s 1.25% exchangeable senior notes due 20=
26, a convertible bond it issued in 2021.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> Section 4.06(e) of the indenture, the 94-page contract governing the b=
onds, says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If, and for so long as, the restri=
ctive legend on the Notes specified in =E2=80=8E=E2=80=8ESection 2.05(c) ha=
s not been removed, the Notes are assigned a restricted CUSIP or the Notes =
are not otherwise freely tradable =E2=80=A6 as of the 370th day after the l=
ast date of original issuance of the Notes, the Company shall pay Additiona=
l Interest on the Notes at a rate equal to 0.50% per annum of the principal=
 amount of Notes outstanding until the restrictive legend on the Notes has =
been removed. =E2=80=A6</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m sorry, this is boring. Now you kno=
w more about the administrative workings of convertible bonds than you ever=
 wanted to. Also though you know more about the administrative workings of =
convertible bonds than Avid=E2=80=99s CFO did last week, <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34603555.257368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
Lmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0vQXJjaGl2ZXMvZWRnYXIvZGF0YS8wMDAwNzA0NTY=
yLzAwMDE2ODMxNjgyNDAwMTM1OS9hdmlkXzhrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB78ba94=
55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> whoops</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On February 29, 2024, Avid Bioservices, Inc. (=
the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) received an acceleration notice (the =E2=80=
=9CAcceleration Notice=E2=80=9D) from a holder of its 1.250% Exchangeable S=
enior Notes due 2026 (the =E2=80=9C2026 Notes=E2=80=9D). The Acceleration N=
otice stipulates, among other things, that (i) the Company did not remove t=
he restrictive legend on the 2026 Notes by March 17, 2022 as required under=
 the indenture governing the 2026 Notes (the =E2=80=9C2026 Notes Indenture=
=E2=80=9D), (ii) due to such failure, additional interest has accrued there=
after at a rate of 0.50% per annum (the =E2=80=9CAdditional Interest=E2=80=
=9D), (iii) such Additional Interest has not been paid by the Company as of=
 the date of the Acceleration Notice, which constitutes an event of default=
 under the 2026 Notes Indenture (the =E2=80=9CEvent of Default=E2=80=9D), a=
nd (iv) such holder is the beneficial owner of at least 25% in aggregate pr=
incipal amount of the outstanding 2026 Notes and therefore has the right to=
 accelerate all of the 2026 Notes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a result of such interest payment default a=
nd pursuant to the terms of the 2026 Notes Indenture, such holder declared =
100% of the principal of, and accrued and unpaid interest on, the 2026 Note=
s to be due and payable immediately (the =E2=80=9CAcceleration Event=E2=80=
=9D). The accelerated amount, inclusive of principal and interest due and p=
ayable, as of February=C2=A029, 2024, the date of acceleration, was approxi=
mately $146.0 million and accrues interest at 2.75% per annum until paid in=
 full.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Company did not receive any notices and wa=
s not otherwise made aware of the Event of Default prior to receipt of the =
Acceleration Notice, and did not have an opportunity to cure the Event of D=
efault at the time of receipt of the Acceleration Notice.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s from a Form 8-K that Avid filed=
 yesterday. Avid forgot, for two years, to take the restrictive legend off =
of its convertible. This was=C2=A0<em>very understandable: </em>Its obligat=
ion to remove the restricted legend was boring and technical and buried in =
Section 4.06(e) of a bond indenture that surely=C2=A0<em>nobody=C2=A0</em>r=
ead.=C2=A0It could only remove the legend a year after it issued the bonds,=
 after everyone had stopped paying attention. And, as Avid points out, it =
=E2=80=9Cdid not receive any notices and was not otherwise made aware=E2=80=
=9D of this provision in, sure, a contract that it signed, but a very long =
and boring contract. (And, to be fair, the holders forgot too!) And because=
 it completely forgot about its obligation to remove the legend, Avid=C2=A0=
<em>also=C2=A0</em>forgot to pay the 0.5% penalty interest rate for two yea=
rs. And because it forgot to pay the extra interest, it created a non-curab=
le default on the bonds: The holders can demand all of their money back, wi=
th interest, immediately, with no chance for Avid to fix the problem by rem=
oving the legend and paying the overdue interest.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
