<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Buffalo man identified in court papers as Ro=
bert W. Johnson =E2=80=94 who sometimes goes by Willie =E2=80=94 has filed =
bankruptcy petitions on behalf of two different publicly traded companies i=
n recent months despite having no authority or basis to do so. Public polic=
y in the US makes them tough to stamp out completely, leaving a confusing t=
rail of public denials and quick dismissals in their wake.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He first took aim at Carrols Restaurant Group,=
 the largest Burger King franchisee in the US, in early February. Shoddy as=
sembly of the snail-mailed petitions didn=E2=80=99t stop them from appearin=
g in official court dockets, however briefly. Then, in recent days he targe=
ted NerdWallet, a personal finance firm with a market value of more than $1=
 billion. NerdWallet called the filing =E2=80=9Cfraudulent and unauthorized=
=E2=80=9D and a judge tossed the petition shortly after.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even the brief existence of such fake filings =
can trigger computer-driven court filing scrapers, leaving incorrect impres=
sions on court watchers including Bloomberg News. Both of Johnson=E2=80=99s=
 filings showed up outside of stock market hours, but NerdWallet=E2=80=99s =
shares still fell for a time when trading opened on Monday.</p>
</blockquote>
